Computer Vision Project

Noah Hicks (nhicks)

I implement AlexNet-like deep, convolutional neural network (CNN) with PyTorch. I use the CNN to classify flowers into the 102 categories.

The project consists of the following parts:

  • Load and prepare data.
  • Load a pretrained Alexnet in PyTorch.
  • Set up transfer learning for flower classification problem
  • Train the model
  • Model performance monitoring and analysis with learning curve
  • Questions regarding the design choices

This is made for my Intro to AI class at Carnegie Mellon University. Some code was provided, some was generated by GPT-5, and some was written by myself. All code is approved by myself.

1.3. Data transformation and processing

In[3]:
# Process with some data transformation, do not change
data_transforms = {
    'training': transforms.Compose([
        transforms.RandomResizedCrop(224),
        transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(),
        transforms.RandomRotation(30),
        transforms.ToTensor(),
        transforms.Normalize([0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
                             [0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
    ]),
    'validation': transforms.Compose([
        transforms.Resize(256),
        transforms.CenterCrop(224),
        transforms.ToTensor(),
        transforms.Normalize([0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
                             [0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
    ]),
    'testing': transforms.Compose([
        transforms.Resize(256),
        transforms.CenterCrop(224),
        transforms.ToTensor(),
        transforms.Normalize([0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
                             [0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
    ])
}
# This specifies how many images to process per training/validation
batch_size = 64

image_datasets = {
    'training': datasets.ImageFolder(train_dir, transform=data_transforms['training']),
    'testing': datasets.ImageFolder(test_dir, transform=data_transforms['testing']),
    'validation': datasets.ImageFolder(valid_dir, transform=data_transforms['validation'])
}

dataloaders = {
    'training': torch.utils.data.DataLoader(image_datasets['training'], batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True, num_workers=4, pin_memory=True),
    'testing': torch.utils.data.DataLoader(image_datasets['testing'], batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=False, num_workers=4, pin_memory=True),
    'validation': torch.utils.data.DataLoader(image_datasets['validation'], batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=False, num_workers=4, pin_memory=True)
}

# get the length of each dataloaders
training_len = len(dataloaders['training'])
test_len = len(dataloaders['testing'])
validation_len = len(dataloaders['validation'])
class_to_idx = image_datasets['training'].class_to_idx

print('We have ', training_len, 'batches of training images;', 'each with', batch_size, 'images')
print('We have ', validation_len, 'batches of validation images;', 'each with', batch_size, 'images')

# Let us preview size of each batch
sample_batch = next(iter(dataloaders['training']))[0]
print('Single batch', sample_batch.shape)

Question 1: What is the effect of random flip and rotation in image data transformation?

  • How does it impact the training?
    • It augments the data so they can effectively create new views of the same flower, and improves the models ability to generalize and keep it from overfitting.
  • Why do we not apply them randomly at the validation or test time?
    • To see their accuracy on the true distrubution of images given in the data.

Question 2: Explain the meaning of these numbers for a single batch

  • 64: batch size is the number of images that are processed together.
  • 3: The number of color channels.
  • 224: After transformations, this is the image height.
  • 224: image width after transformations.

# In transfer learning, we freeze the feature parameters from the original model
# The most straightforward way is to freeze their gradient update
# see https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/generated/torch.Tensor.requires_grad.html for how to set it
for param in model.features.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = False

  (features): Sequential(

    (4): ReLU(inplace=True)
    (5): MaxPool2d(kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=0, dilation=1, ceil_mode=False)

    (7): ReLU(inplace=True)

    (9): ReLU(inplace=True)
    (10): Conv2d(256, 256, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1))
    (11): ReLU(inplace=True)
    (12): MaxPool2d(kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=0, dilation=1, ceil_mode=False)
  )
  (avgpool): AdaptiveAvgPool2d(output_size=(6, 6))
  (classifier): Sequential(
    (0): Dropout(p=0.5, inplace=False)
    (1): Linear(in_features=9216, out_features=4096, bias=True)
    (2): ReLU(inplace=True)
    (3): Dropout(p=0.5, inplace=False)
    (4): Linear(in_features=4096, out_features=4096, bias=True)
    (5): ReLU(inplace=True)
    (6): Linear(in_features=4096, out_features=1000, bias=True)
  )
)

In[6]:
# now we need to replace the classifier by our datasets
# Note, fc2's out_feature should match our number of classes, which is 102

# Tip: check the original AlexNet classifier for some thoughts; they are similar.

# Defining number of hidden units in our fully connected layer
hidden_units = 1024
number_of_flowers = len(class_to_idx)

# Number of input features from the pretrained classifier
input_features = model.classifier[1].in_features

# Defining the fully connected layer that will be trained on the flower images
classifier = nn.Sequential(OrderedDict([
    ('fc1', nn.Linear(input_features, hidden_units)),
    ('relu', nn.ReLU(inplace=True)),
    ('dropout', nn.Dropout(0.5)),
    ('fc2', nn.Linear(hidden_units, number_of_flowers)),
    ('output', nn.LogSoftmax(dim=1))
]))
model.classifier = classifier

    (3): Conv2d(64, 192, kernel_size=(5, 5), stride=(1, 1), padding=(2, 2))

    (5): MaxPool2d(kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=0, dilation=1, ceil_mode=False)

)

1.6. Set up the configurations and train it!

  • epochs = 30
  • since it is a multiclassification problem, we use negative log likelihood loss
  • we use the Adam optimizer
  • learning rate (lr) = 0.001

In each epoch, we go through all the training samples to update the model, and evaluate with the validation samples to see how good the current model is.

  • accuracy: mean of the matches in predicted class and the labels
  • loss: negative log likelihood loss

Sample outputs are provided below; but yours may vary Your validation accuracy may be better than train; this is fine

In[8]:
device = torch.device('cuda:0' if torch.cuda.is_available() else 'cpu')
model.to(device)

epochs = 15
optimizer = optim.Adam(model.classifier.parameters(), lr=0.0005)
criterion = nn.NLLLoss()
print_every = 5

validation_accuracies, training_accuracies = [], []
validation_losses, training_losses = [], []

best_validation_accuracy = 0.0
best_model_weights = None

for e in range(epochs):

    training_loss = 0.0
    training_accuracy = 0.0
    validation_loss = 0.0
    validation_accuracy = 0.0

    model.train()
    for batch_idx, (images, labels) in enumerate(dataloaders['training']):
        images, labels = images.to(device), labels.to(device)

        optimizer.zero_grad()
        log_ps = model(images)
        loss = criterion(log_ps, labels)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()

        ps = torch.exp(log_ps)
        top_ps, top_class = ps.topk(1, dim=1)
        matches = top_class.eq(labels.view_as(top_class)).float()
        train_batch_accuracy = matches.mean().item()

        training_loss += loss.item()
        training_accuracy += train_batch_accuracy

        if batch_idx % print_every == 0:
            print('epoch', e, 'batch', batch_idx)
            print('training loss per batch', loss.item())
            print('training accuracy per batch', train_batch_accuracy)

    model.eval()
    with torch.no_grad():
        for images, labels in dataloaders['validation']:
            images, labels = images.to(device), labels.to(device)
            log_ps = model(images)
            loss = criterion(log_ps, labels)
            ps = torch.exp(log_ps)
            top_ps, top_class = ps.topk(1, dim=1)
            matches = top_class.eq(labels.view_as(top_class)).float()
            validation_batch_accuracy = matches.mean().item()

            validation_loss += loss.item()
            validation_accuracy += validation_batch_accuracy

    epoch_training_loss = training_loss / training_len
    epoch_training_accuracy = training_accuracy / training_len
    epoch_validation_loss = validation_loss / validation_len
    epoch_validation_accuracy = validation_accuracy / validation_len

    if epoch_validation_accuracy >= best_validation_accuracy:
        best_validation_accuracy = epoch_validation_accuracy
        best_model_weights = deepcopy(model.state_dict())

    print('epoch', e, 'summary')
    print('avg training loss per epoch', epoch_training_loss)
    print('avg training accuracy per epoch', epoch_training_accuracy)
    print('avg validation loss per epoch', epoch_validation_loss)
    print('avg validation accuracy per epoch', epoch_validation_accuracy)

    training_losses.append(epoch_training_loss)
    training_accuracies.append(epoch_training_accuracy)
    validation_losses.append(epoch_validation_loss)
    validation_accuracies.append(epoch_validation_accuracy)
    print()

1.8. Predict on the test data with the best model so far

In[11]:
# Predict on the test data

model.load_state_dict(best_model_weights)
model.eval()

correct_predictions = 0
samples_seen = 0

predictions = []
label_data = []

with torch.no_grad():
    for images, labels in dataloaders['testing']:
        images, labels = images.to(device), labels.to(device)
        log_ps = model(images)
        ps = torch.exp(log_ps)
        top_ps, top_class = ps.topk(1, dim=1)
        matches = top_class.eq(labels.view_as(top_class)).float()

        correct_predictions += matches.sum().item()
        samples_seen += labels.size(0)

        predictions.extend(top_class.cpu().numpy().flatten())
        label_data.extend(labels.cpu().numpy().flatten())

print('Test Accuracy:', correct_predictions / samples_seen)

Test Accuracy: 0.851037851037851

Question 7: Now normalize the raw confusion matrix reported in the previous question by dividing each row by the sum of all its elements. Include this normalized confusion matrix in your report. It may look small but that is fine. What does the diagnal denote in the normalized confusion matrix? What is the meaning of the number in the row 1 column 2?

  • The diagonal shows the per class accuracy and the ratio of true predictions the model makes.
  • That represents the ratio of class one samples that are misclassified as class 2.

# Please plot the confusion matrix other than print() if possible
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix as conf_mat
import numpy as np

cf = conf_mat(label_data, predictions)

print('confusion matrix')
print(cf)
print()
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.imshow(cf, interpolation='nearest', cmap=plt.cm.Blues)
plt.title('Confusion Matrix (Counts)')
plt.colorbar()
plt.xlabel('Predicted Label Index')
plt.ylabel('True Label Index')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# normalized confusion matrix
print('normalized confusion matrix')
row_sums = cf.sum(axis=1, keepdims=True)
with np.errstate(divide='ignore', invalid='ignore'):
    ncf = np.divide(cf, row_sums, where=row_sums != 0)
ncf = np.nan_to_num(ncf)
print(ncf)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.imshow(ncf, interpolation='nearest', cmap=plt.cm.Oranges)
plt.title('Normalized Confusion Matrix')
plt.colorbar()
plt.xlabel('Predicted Label Index')
plt.ylabel('True Label Index')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Question 8: Transfer Learning

  • What is the purpose of a pretrained model and why should it work?
    • The purpose is to bring in an existing model with rich extractors to determine various visual features that are then reporposed to classify flowers (in this case). It should work because the model is already good at discerning between generic types of visual patterns.
  • Why should we freeze the features' gradient in the pretrained model but only update the classifier?
    • This is done so the generic features remain stable while we work on the classifier for our 102 flower classes.
  • What may happen if we do not freeze the features' gradient?
    • If we did not freeze it, it's possible that the model overfits or forget various representations. So it would take much longer to train and be less useful.
